00:43:56.230 --> 00:43:57.750
It's not zero marginal cost.

00:43:57.750 --> 00:44:01.420
I cannot produce more energy
that I want without putting

00:44:01.420 --> 00:44:03.270
on more panels,
which has a cost.

00:44:03.270 --> 00:44:05.300
But it's zero in
the sense of I'm

00:44:05.300 --> 00:44:08.850
not consuming things--
like with coal, right?

00:44:08.850 --> 00:44:11.090
So I wasn't sure which
of those two distinctions

00:44:11.090 --> 00:44:14.460
you were talking about, and how
you get to zero in that regard.

00:44:14.460 --> 00:44:16.720
And then I didn't understand
it at all in logistics,

00:44:16.720 --> 00:44:19.220
because as far as I know, you
still have to drive miles.

00:44:19.220 --> 00:44:20.942
And that cost isn't
really changing.

00:44:20.942 --> 00:44:22.900
JEREMY RIFKIN: Let's talk
about the solar panel

00:44:22.900 --> 00:44:25.830
or the wind turbine or
the geothermal heat pump.

00:44:25.830 --> 00:44:28.690
You have to pay the fixed cost
of the harvesting technology.

00:44:28.690 --> 00:44:31.023
It probably is going to take
you somewhere between three

00:44:31.023 --> 00:44:33.190
and nine years to pay
back on the solar panels.

00:44:33.190 --> 00:44:36.820
But the moment that channel's
up, you keep it clean,

00:44:36.820 --> 00:44:37.760
the sun is free.

00:44:37.760 --> 00:44:38.810
Coal is not free.

00:44:38.810 --> 00:44:40.600
Natural gas, shale gas, uranium?

00:44:40.600 --> 00:44:41.950
None of that's free.

00:44:41.950 --> 00:44:42.980
But the sun is free.

00:44:42.980 --> 00:44:43.814
You just capture it.

00:44:43.814 --> 00:44:44.521
The wind is free.

00:44:44.521 --> 00:44:45.220
You capture it.

00:44:45.220 --> 00:44:46.510
The geothermal heat's free.

00:44:46.510 --> 00:44:47.710
You capture it.

00:44:47.710 --> 00:44:49.280
So in that sense,
it's near zero.

00:44:49.280 --> 00:44:52.210
But you're only
advantaged if you're

00:44:52.210 --> 00:44:55.630
in an energy internet that's
part of an internet of things.

00:44:55.630 --> 00:44:57.370
Because you may
have a lull one day

00:44:57.370 --> 00:44:59.920
where the sun isn't
shining, and you

00:44:59.920 --> 00:45:01.650
haven't stored that
green electricity.

00:45:01.650 --> 00:45:03.370
Or maybe the wind's
blowing at night,

00:45:03.370 --> 00:45:05.700
but you need electricity
during the day.

00:45:05.700 --> 00:45:08.040
So we have to create
an energy internet that

00:45:08.040 --> 00:45:09.332
crosses continents.

00:45:09.332 --> 00:45:11.540
And that way, let's say in
Eastern Europe, where it's

00:45:11.540 --> 00:45:13.040
night time, they
have a lot of wind?

00:45:13.040 --> 00:45:14.880
The surplus goes up
on the energy internet

00:45:14.880 --> 00:45:17.160
to the places which
are still daytime.

00:45:17.160 --> 00:45:19.740
Or if you have a lot of
sun somewhere in Europe,

00:45:19.740 --> 00:45:21.570
in Western Europe,
during the day,

00:45:21.570 --> 00:45:24.150
you put the surplus up on
the net and that energy,

00:45:24.150 --> 00:45:27.340
and then it would take it
to another part of Europe.

00:45:27.340 --> 00:45:29.180
So these energies
are intermittent.

00:45:29.180 --> 00:45:31.630
And they change in
different times of day

00:45:31.630 --> 00:45:33.540
in different parts
of a continent.

00:45:33.540 --> 00:45:35.740
To the extent that we
have an energy internet,

00:45:35.740 --> 00:45:38.470
we can share our surpluses
when other has lulls.

00:45:38.470 --> 00:45:41.085
And we can-- if we store
it correctly, hydrogen

00:45:41.085 --> 00:45:44.930
and other storage technologies--
we can deal with peak loads,

00:45:44.930 --> 00:45:46.210
base loads across continents.

00:45:46.210 --> 00:45:48.800
That's we're attempting to
do in Germany and in Europe

00:45:48.800 --> 00:45:49.850
right now.

00:45:49.850 --> 00:45:52.830
And I was just in China.

00:45:52.830 --> 00:45:54.620
That was a big surprise
to me with China,

00:45:54.620 --> 00:45:57.387
because I didn't think they
were going to be players.

00:45:57.387 --> 00:45:59.470
"The Third Industrial
Revolution," my former book,

00:45:59.470 --> 00:46:01.520
was published there
two years ago.

00:46:01.520 --> 00:46:03.280
And the new premiere
read it in English,

00:46:03.280 --> 00:46:04.990
and instructed the
government to now

00:46:04.990 --> 00:46:08.250
move on a distributed
energy internet

00:46:08.250 --> 00:46:11.080
and to move toward an
internet of things.

00:46:11.080 --> 00:46:13.370
I was there in September
with the leadership.

00:46:13.370 --> 00:46:16.680
10 weeks later-- 10 weeks
later-- after my meetings

00:46:16.680 --> 00:46:19.380
with government leadership,
the Chinese government

00:46:19.380 --> 00:46:23.130
announced an $80 billion
four-year commitment

00:46:23.130 --> 00:46:26.250
to move the distributed
energy internet across China

00:46:26.250 --> 00:46:28.560
so everyone could
produce their own energy.

00:46:28.560 --> 00:46:32.140
By contrast, the US is going
to try to raise $3.5 billion

00:46:32.140 --> 00:46:35.630
over 20 years for a
centralized smart grid.

00:46:35.630 --> 00:46:37.920
So I'm guardedly hopeful.

00:46:37.920 --> 00:46:40.140
But I think that these
are real challenges.

00:46:40.140 --> 00:46:43.010
And for you, the challenge
is your up-front cost.

00:46:43.010 --> 00:46:45.480
So you can pay them off, and
get to your marginal cost

00:46:45.480 --> 00:46:46.230
being nearly free.

00:46:46.230 --> 00:46:48.212
It's a challenge.

00:46:48.212 --> 00:46:49.670
AUDIENCE: What
about the logistics?

00:46:49.670 --> 00:46:50.600
Can you explain that?

00:46:50.600 --> 00:46:52.690
JEREMY RIFKIN: That's the newest
one, that's the newest one.

00:46:52.690 --> 00:46:54.065
And I deal with
that in the book.

00:46:54.065 --> 00:46:55.590
It's brand new, last 24 months.

00:46:55.590 --> 00:46:57.364
We're dealing with
now, in Nord Calais,

00:46:57.364 --> 00:46:59.780
we're doing a master plan for
the oldest industrial region

00:46:59.780 --> 00:47:00.580
of France.

00:47:00.580 --> 00:47:03.300
And they have Dunkirk,
a port facility.

00:47:03.300 --> 00:47:05.730
The logistics is the
most inefficient part

00:47:05.730 --> 00:47:06.610
of the value chain.

00:47:06.610 --> 00:47:08.170
That's why it's costly.

00:47:08.170 --> 00:47:10.140
You have freight
across the country.

00:47:10.140 --> 00:47:13.190
When you see a truck, sometimes
it's only 20%, 30% full.

00:47:13.190 --> 00:47:15.610
Or it's dead and heading
back with no cargo.

00:47:15.610 --> 00:47:17.770
It's not systematized.

00:47:17.770 --> 00:47:20.640
It's not efficient.

00:47:20.640 --> 00:47:23.180
What we're looking
at now is a transport

00:47:23.180 --> 00:47:25.850
and logistics
automated internet.

00:47:25.850 --> 00:47:30.820
And this would allow you to
have everything modularized

00:47:30.820 --> 00:47:33.950
so that you can move
shipments to any distribution

00:47:33.950 --> 00:47:34.980
center you want.

00:47:34.980 --> 00:47:38.460
For example, there are 5,000
warehouse is in the US.

00:47:38.460 --> 00:47:39.430
So what?

00:47:39.430 --> 00:47:41.440
If you're a big company,
vertically integrated,

00:47:41.440 --> 00:47:43.080
you own maybe 20 of them.

00:47:43.080 --> 00:47:45.640
So you have to send your
stuff way out of the way,

00:47:45.640 --> 00:47:48.330
hold it there, and then
take it to the destination.

00:47:48.330 --> 00:47:51.560
But what if all 5,000
warehouses, privately-owned,

00:47:51.560 --> 00:47:53.440
came together in a cooperative?

00:47:53.440 --> 00:47:58.310
So when they had space, it
would be open to anybody.

00:47:58.310 --> 00:47:59.220
You follow me?

00:47:59.220 --> 00:48:01.560
Then with 5,000
distribution centers,

00:48:01.560 --> 00:48:03.450
you could move to
whichever one you wanted,

00:48:03.450 --> 00:48:07.540
and save a huge amount
of your transport time

00:48:07.540 --> 00:48:09.900
moving it through the
system with GPS guidance.

00:48:09.900 --> 00:48:12.387
But you'd have to have all
the containers modularized.

00:48:12.387 --> 00:48:14.470
Everything would have to
be on the same standards,

00:48:14.470 --> 00:48:16.870
so you can move the package
across that internet

00:48:16.870 --> 00:48:19.950
like you move all the packages
across the communication

00:48:19.950 --> 00:48:20.900
internet.

00:48:20.900 --> 00:48:24.120
And then if you can move to
driverless vehicles and drones,

00:48:24.120 --> 00:48:27.950
that's going to reduce your
labor costs substantially.

00:48:27.950 --> 00:48:30.730
So you'll get toward
zero, but it'll still

00:48:30.730 --> 00:48:33.050
be marginal cost, but
fairly low compared

00:48:33.050 --> 00:48:34.490
to the cost we have now.

00:48:34.490 --> 00:48:35.120
It's exciting.

00:48:35.120 --> 00:48:37.350
We're just beginning this
discussion in the last 24

00:48:37.350 --> 00:48:37.970
months.

00:48:37.970 --> 00:48:40.303
We're laying down the first
plan in northern France now.

00:48:40.303 --> 00:48:42.879
So we're on a learning curve.

00:48:42.879 --> 00:48:43.420
