we did not see cell phones
coming to sub-Saharan Africa

00:49:22.054 --> 00:49:22.720
and rural India.

00:49:22.720 --> 00:49:23.219
We didn't.

00:49:23.219 --> 00:49:24.910
It was never in the equation.

00:49:24.910 --> 00:49:28.090
All of a sudden, without any
marketing, millions of people

00:49:28.090 --> 00:49:29.370
starting getting cell phones.

00:49:29.370 --> 00:49:31.260
Then the cell towers came.

00:49:31.260 --> 00:49:36.200
And what we realized there was
the liability in the developing

00:49:36.200 --> 00:49:38.570
world is actually their asset.

00:49:38.570 --> 00:49:40.500
They have no infrastructure.

00:49:40.500 --> 00:49:43.260
It's easier and quicker
financially to build

00:49:43.260 --> 00:49:45.832
from scratch then to mend
an old infrastructure.

00:49:45.832 --> 00:49:46.540
It's like a home.

00:49:46.540 --> 00:49:48.880
My wife and I have a
beautiful old home.

00:49:48.880 --> 00:49:52.900
We spent 24 years trying
to renovate this home.

00:49:52.900 --> 00:49:55.450
It's a big entropic
pit-- sorry, honey--

00:49:55.450 --> 00:49:56.770
but it's an entropic pit.

00:49:56.770 --> 00:49:59.030
Had we built a new
house from scratch

00:49:59.030 --> 00:50:00.820
in six months, much cheaper.

00:50:00.820 --> 00:50:03.407
So the United
Nations has embraced

00:50:03.407 --> 00:50:05.240
the five-pillar, Third
Industrial Revolution

00:50:05.240 --> 00:50:08.090
plan we've laid out toward
this internet of things.

00:50:08.090 --> 00:50:08.970
Why?

00:50:08.970 --> 00:50:11.380
They think the developing
world can move quicker.

00:50:11.380 --> 00:50:14.200
Now in rural India, in the
last 24 months, and now

00:50:14.200 --> 00:50:17.270
sub-Saharan Africa, young people
your age, startup companies,

00:50:17.270 --> 00:50:19.570
are all over the map
in the rural areas.

00:50:19.570 --> 00:50:21.560
And they're setting
up little micro grids.

00:50:21.560 --> 00:50:24.550
$2,000 for a village,
you wire up the huts.

00:50:24.550 --> 00:50:26.170
You put solar panels on.

00:50:26.170 --> 00:50:27.025
You lease the panel.

00:50:27.025 --> 00:50:29.010
When it's paid back, it's yours.

00:50:29.010 --> 00:50:34.000
And a village, a small village
of several hundred? $2,000.

00:50:34.000 --> 00:50:37.070
So you can set up micro grids,
and it works like Wi-Fi.

00:50:37.070 --> 00:50:40.294
You start connecting these
small players together,

00:50:40.294 --> 00:50:41.960
and all of a sudden,
you have a network.

00:50:41.960 --> 00:50:45.740
Just like a Wi-Fi network, you
have a near zero marginal cost

00:50:45.740 --> 00:50:48.760
energy micro grid network,
and you create from the bottom

00:50:48.760 --> 00:50:50.786
out, not from the top down.

00:50:50.786 --> 00:50:51.910
That's beginning to happen.

00:50:51.910 --> 00:50:53.250
It's pretty encouraging.

00:50:53.250 --> 00:50:57.380
As to the haves and
have nots, let me say,

00:50:57.380 --> 00:50:59.540
I taught the advanced
management program

00:50:59.540 --> 00:51:04.150
at Wharton for 16 years, our
CEO program, nearly 16 years.

00:51:04.150 --> 00:51:06.900
We all believed-- in the
First and Second Industrial

00:51:06.900 --> 00:51:10.360
Revolution, we had to
vertically integrate

00:51:10.360 --> 00:51:13.230
our business activity.

00:51:13.230 --> 00:51:16.040
Every society needs
three things in order

00:51:16.040 --> 00:51:17.740
to organize itself
as a society--

00:51:17.740 --> 00:51:20.300
a form of communication,
a form of power,

00:51:20.300 --> 00:51:22.350
and a form of mobility.

00:51:22.350 --> 00:51:24.570
When communication comes
together with energy,

00:51:24.570 --> 00:51:25.730
they create new systems.

00:51:25.730 --> 00:51:28.160
For example, the 19th
century, the communication,

00:51:28.160 --> 00:51:29.960
we went to steam-powered
printing-- cheap,

00:51:29.960 --> 00:51:33.090
efficient, mass-produced
printing-- and the telegraph.

00:51:33.090 --> 00:51:36.394
That allowed us to manage
a complex coal power

00:51:36.394 --> 00:51:37.310
industrial revolution.

00:51:37.310 --> 00:51:38.680
That was the power source.

00:51:38.680 --> 00:51:41.510
And then we introduced the
locomotive for the mobility

00:51:41.510 --> 00:51:44.020
so we could bring dense urban
areas together and create

00:51:44.020 --> 00:51:45.320
national markets.

00:51:45.320 --> 00:51:47.230
20th century, Second
Industrial Revolution,

00:51:47.230 --> 00:51:49.480
the form of communication
was centralized electricity,

00:51:49.480 --> 00:51:52.770
the telephone, then
radio and television,

00:51:52.770 --> 00:51:57.600
to organize a power
source-- oil--

00:51:57.600 --> 00:52:02.210
and a new mobility factor called
the internal combustion engine.

00:52:02.210 --> 00:52:04.570
The Third Industrial
Revolution, the communication

00:52:04.570 --> 00:52:07.390
is the internet and
the internet of things.

00:52:07.390 --> 00:52:09.170
The power source is
the energy internet

00:52:09.170 --> 00:52:11.710
and renewables that are
distributed energies.

00:52:11.710 --> 00:52:15.410
And the mobility is an
automated, driverless transport

00:52:15.410 --> 00:52:18.760
and logistics system
in one platform.

00:52:18.760 --> 00:52:20.840
So I think the trend
lines are there.

00:52:20.840 --> 00:52:22.950
But what it allows
us to do now is

00:52:22.950 --> 00:52:25.670
eliminate vertically-integrated
global companies

00:52:25.670 --> 00:52:29.000
where-- they were essentially in
the First and Second Industrial

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:31.111
Revolution, because they
reduced marginal cost.

00:52:31.111 --> 00:52:32.610
They eliminated a
lot of middle men.

00:52:32.610 --> 00:52:34.270
You put everything
under one roof.

00:52:34.270 --> 00:52:37.190
But now the internet of things
allows millions of people

00:52:37.190 --> 00:52:40.880
to even bypass those types
of vertical organizations,

00:52:40.880 --> 00:52:43.730
scale laterally, eliminate
all the middle men,

00:52:43.730 --> 00:52:45.270
and you directly
engage each other.

00:52:45.270 --> 00:52:46.810
That's what the
internet's about.

00:52:46.810 --> 00:52:49.670
Millions of people go up there
in lateral economies of scale.

00:52:49.670 --> 00:52:52.605
They are bypassing-- thanks to
Google and all these others--

00:52:52.605 --> 00:52:54.520
they're bypassing
all the middlemen

00:52:54.520 --> 00:52:56.160
with information goods.

00:52:56.160 --> 00:52:58.660
Now they're going to be able,
with these lateral economies

00:52:58.660 --> 00:53:01.680
of scale, to also
move to the world--

00:53:01.680 --> 00:53:05.490
the physical world-- energy
and 3D printed products.

00:53:05.490 --> 00:53:08.120
And so I should say, things
like CouchSurfing and Airbnb

00:53:08.120 --> 00:53:10.050
are just the beginning
of this shift.

00:53:10.050 --> 00:53:13.650
But what it does is it
democratizes the economy.

00:53:13.650 --> 00:53:15.730
And hopefully, you'll
be in a world in 2050

00:53:15.730 --> 00:53:18.620
that won't be the 1% or the 99%.

00:53:18.620 --> 00:53:21.780
It'll be a shared economy,
a sustainable good quality

00:53:21.780 --> 00:53:23.940
of life, where no
one's left behind.

00:53:23.940 --> 00:53:25.050
Now, is it Utopia?

00:53:25.050 --> 00:53:25.550
No.

00:53:25.550 --> 00:53:27.990
Will we actually get
everything I'm laying out?

00:53:27.990 --> 00:53:28.950
Doubtful.

00:53:28.950 --> 00:53:31.870
But if we can at least see
this as a possible narrative,

00:53:31.870 --> 00:53:34.530
it's a pretty good journey
to be on even if we only

00:53:34.530 --> 00:53:36.020
get half of it done.

00:53:36.020 --> 00:53:39.230
And it's a lot better
journey than we're on now,

00:53:39.230 --> 00:53:42.530
where we have a Second
Industrial Revolution that's

00:53:42.530 --> 00:53:45.350
bringing us mass unemployment,
a greater disparity

00:53:45.350 --> 00:53:47.750
between rich and poor, and
climate change threatening

00:53:47.750 --> 00:53:48.910
our survival.

00:53:48.910 --> 00:53:53.270
So I think this new journey
is a positive journey.

00:53:53.270 --> 00:53:56.420
It's going to be fraught
with problems and challenges.

00:53:56.420 --> 00:53:57.860
But it's worthy
of your generation

00:53:57.860 --> 00:53:59.651
to help reheal the
planet and create a more

00:53:59.651 --> 00:54:03.330
just world for all
of us, hopefully.

00:54:03.330 --> 00:54:05.560
AUDIENCE: So I had
a question again

00:54:05.560 --> 00:54:06.969
about zero marginal cost--

00:54:06.969 --> 00:54:08.010
JEREMY RIFKIN: Near zero.

00:54:08.010 --> 00:54:09.620
AUDIENCE: Or new zero.

00:54:09.620 --> 00:54:12.557
I work in manufacturing, and
we use 3D printing quite a bit.

00:54:12.557 --> 00:54:14.390
But the thing that we
like about 3D printing

00:54:14.390 --> 00:54:16.750
is that it's a very low
fixed cost in exchange

00:54:16.750 --> 00:54:20.260
for a much higher marginal cost.

00:54:20.260 --> 00:54:23.000
So marginal cost for
current manufacturing

00:54:23.000 --> 00:54:25.010
is already very, very
low-- much, much lower

00:54:25.010 --> 00:54:27.780
than 3D printing will ever get.

00:54:27.780 --> 00:54:30.740
So I guess maybe
I'm misunderstanding

00:54:30.740 --> 00:54:34.457
what you mean by the near zero
marginal cost on manufacturing?

00:54:34.457 --> 00:54:36.290
JEREMY RIFKIN: My
understanding-- of course,

00:54:36.290 --> 00:54:37.450
the printers are pretty cheap.

00:54:37.450 --> 00:54:38.600
But they're not
very sophisticated.

00:54:38.600 --> 00:54:40.190
You can get a printer
now for $1,200.

00:54:40.190 --> 00:54:42.010
The big, sophisticated
printers cost more.

00:54:42.010 --> 00:54:42.718
But you're right.

00:54:42.718 --> 00:54:45.260
It's an exponential curve.

00:54:45.260 --> 00:54:47.552
The fixed costs are going to
really go down, especially

00:54:47.552 --> 00:54:49.051
because it's added
at manufacturing.

00:54:49.051 --> 00:54:50.852
AUDIENCE: They're
already much, much lower.

00:54:50.852 --> 00:54:52.122
JEREMY RIFKIN: Yeah.

00:54:52.122 --> 00:54:53.580
AUDIENCE: And this
is in a typical,

00:54:53.580 --> 00:54:55.670
like a traditional
manufacturing line.

00:54:55.670 --> 00:54:57.670
JEREMY RIFKIN: What
brings the marginal cost

00:54:57.670 --> 00:55:00.260
down is its additive
manufacturing.

00:55:00.260 --> 00:55:02.320
I always taught
subtractive manufacturing

00:55:02.320 --> 00:55:06.120
would, in centralized first and
second Industrial Revolution

00:55:06.120 --> 00:55:09.200
factories, you take a big hunk
of a material from nature,

00:55:09.200 --> 00:55:12.496
cut it up, tear it down,
winnow it, and then put

00:55:12.496 --> 00:55:13.370
the product together.

00:55:13.370 --> 00:55:14.740
And you throw a lot out.

00:55:14.740 --> 00:55:15.700
All right?

00:55:15.700 --> 00:55:19.140
As you know, with 3D printing,
the software is directing

00:55:19.140 --> 00:55:21.110
the molten material
to, layer by layer,

00:55:21.110 --> 00:55:24.080
build up a three dimensional
product with moving parts.

00:55:24.080 --> 00:55:25.430
It's additive manufacturing.

00:55:25.430 --> 00:55:28.180
It uses, what, 1/10
of the material?

00:55:28.180 --> 00:55:31.800
With additive manufacturing, you
are using a lot less materials.

00:55:31.800 --> 00:55:34.820
But you're talking about
the materials themselves.

00:55:34.820 --> 00:55:36.430
What I'm saying
is that what I've

00:55:36.430 --> 00:55:38.160
been seeing in the
industry-- in Europe,

00:55:38.160 --> 00:55:41.160
at least-- is they're using
a lot of recycled plastic

00:55:41.160 --> 00:55:44.140
now, which is very low cost.

00:55:44.140 --> 00:55:45.772
And they're now
using, as you know,

00:55:45.772 --> 00:55:47.330
in the Scandinavian
countries they're

00:55:47.330 --> 00:55:51.210
using recycled paper,
which is low marginal cost.

00:55:51.210 --> 00:55:54.050
And we now have some printers
that are using gravel, rocks,

00:55:54.050 --> 00:55:56.220
and sand for various
things, which

00:55:56.220 --> 00:55:57.816
is just locally available.

00:55:57.816 --> 00:55:59.190
I think it's going
to be a while.

00:55:59.190 --> 00:56:02.170
This is so new-- and you're at
the cutting edge of it here--

00:56:02.170 --> 00:56:07.210
it's going to be a while before
3D planning is on center stage.

00:56:07.210 --> 00:56:09.570
But at least the kind
of work you're doing,

00:56:09.570 --> 00:56:11.570
I'm sure you feel very
positive that it's

00:56:11.570 --> 00:56:13.840
going to lead to a new kind
of manufacturing that's

00:56:13.840 --> 00:56:17.026
going to reduce both fixed and
marginal cost down the line.

00:56:17.026 --> 00:56:18.150
It's going to take a while.

00:56:18.150 --> 00:56:20.470
Otherwise, why do it?

00:56:20.470 --> 00:56:23.140
I'm hopeful that
here at Google, help

00:56:23.140 --> 00:56:25.714
lead us into this new world.

00:56:25.714 --> 00:56:27.380
We need to join
together, all the people

00:56:27.380 --> 00:56:29.800
on the planet, with
this new technology,

00:56:29.800 --> 00:56:31.730
and hopefully create some hope.

00:56:31.730 --> 00:56:35.310
Because I see a lot of
despair, a lot of cynicism,

00:56:35.310 --> 00:56:37.120
a sense that nothing can happen.

00:56:37.120 --> 00:56:40.240
But we're right now on the cusp
of a great economic revolution,

00:56:40.240 --> 00:56:42.770
this shift to the collaborate
comments and an internet

00:56:42.770 --> 00:56:46.050
of things platform that allow
us to begin to produce and share

00:56:46.050 --> 00:56:49.090
goods and services with
low or zero marginal cost,

00:56:49.090 --> 00:56:51.450
and in a sustainable
way for the planet.

00:56:51.450 --> 00:56:53.520
It's the journey we
all ought to be on.

00:56:53.520 --> 00:56:54.420
Thank you.

00:56:54.420 --> 00:56:58.789
[APPLAUSE]

